# =============================================================================
# v0.7 demo: ai.glass — effects for AI model calls.
#
# Glass treats every call into an external model — LLM, classifier, vision
# system — as an effect labeled !{Inference}. Same machinery as !{IO} and
# !{Random}: visible at every call site, propagated through call chains,
# auditable at a glance from the type signature.
#
# Why this matters. A post-AI codebase will have model calls scattered
# throughout. Knowing which functions touch a model — and which don't —
# is exactly what auditors, debuggers, and tooling need to reason about
# program behavior. Effect typing makes that question answerable from
# signatures alone, with no source-grepping or runtime tracing.
#
# Model output is untrusted by default. Refinement types describe the
# postcondition a Glass program needs the output to satisfy. The boundary
# between "what the model returned" and "what the program is willing to
# work with" becomes a type-system fact.
# =============================================================================

# --- The simplest case ---------------------------------------------------

# A pure-data wrapper around model_call. Signature alone tells the reader:
# this fn touches a model. Nothing else.
fn ask(prompt: String) : String !{Inference} = model_call(prompt)


# --- Effect composition --------------------------------------------------

# ask + print = !{IO, Inference}. The reader of the signature now knows
# everything that can happen when this fn is called: an external model is
# invoked AND something gets written to the world. Two effects, both
# visible, no surprises.
fn ask_and_show(prompt: String) : String !{IO, Inference} =
  let answer : String = model_call(prompt) in
  print("answer: " ++ answer)


# --- Trust boundary: refinement-checked model output --------------------

# Model output is untrusted. Wrap it in a refinement that states the
# postcondition Glass code expects. If the model returns something that
# violates the refinement, the program raises at the boundary — not 50
# functions later when an empty string triggers a confusing crash.
#
# The refinement is the contract. The model is the supplier. Glass enforces.
fn ask_nonempty(prompt: String) : String !{Inference} =
  let answer : String where (string_length(answer) >= 1) = model_call(prompt) in
  answer


# --- Effect-polymorphic batching ----------------------------------------

# map is effect-polymorphic, so batching a model call across a list of
# prompts gives !{Inference} automatically. No new abstraction needed.
# The same primitive works whether the callback is pure, !{IO}, !{Random},
# or !{Inference}.
fn batch_ask(prompts: List<String>) : List<String> !{Inference} =
  map(prompts, fn(p: String) -> model_call(p))


# --- A pipeline ---------------------------------------------------------

# Compose: ask the model, prefix the answer, print it.
# Effects accumulate to !{IO, Inference}.
fn pipeline(prompt: String) : String !{IO, Inference} =
  let raw : String = model_call(prompt) in
  let tagged : String = "[verified] " ++ raw in
  print(tagged)


# --- Run the demo --------------------------------------------------------

let r1 : String = ask("the simplest case")
let _  : String = print("ask:        " ++ r1)

let _  : String = ask_and_show("compose IO with Inference")

let r3 : String = ask_nonempty("nonempty-by-refinement")
let _  : String = print("refined:    " ++ r3)

let r4 : List<String> = batch_ask(["alpha", "beta", "gamma"])
let _  : String = print("batch[0]:   " ++ match r4 {
  []               => "(empty)";
  [first, ...rest] => first
})

let _  : String = pipeline("the full pipeline")


# Notes for the reader:
#
# - !{Inference} is just a label. Glass doesn't ship an LLM backend. The
#   model_call built-in is a mock that prefixes its input with "[model]:".
#   In a real deployment, model_call dispatches to whatever inference
#   provider the runtime is wired to. The TYPE-LEVEL story is the part
#   that's load-bearing.
#
# - Why refinement-types-on-output instead of structured parsing? Because
#   refinements compose with effects. The signature of ask_nonempty says
#   exactly: "this fn calls a model AND its result is nonempty." A schema
#   library could check the second half but not the first; refinements
#   put both in one place.
#
# - Why a separate effect label instead of overloading IO? Because the
#   audit questions are different. "Did this code call a model?" is
#   answered by inspecting !{Inference} occurrences. "Did this code
#   write to the world?" is !{IO}. Conflating them loses signal.
